  "text": "In Table 1 , we compare the above approximation against the fluid approximate model from [CITATION_1] and from our earlier Markov model in [CITATION_2] . The link speeds were set to 10 Gbps so that the queuing is negligible. The packet sizes were set to 1050 bytes which is the default value in ns2. We see that, unlike TCP Reno and TCP Compound, the average window size for TCP CUBIC depends on the RTT of the flow and increases with RTT. This behaviour makes TCP CUBIC fairer to flows with larger RTT as compared to TCP Reno and TCP Compound. In this case, the average errors for the deterministic loss model in [CITATION_3] , for the Markov chain model in [CITATION_4] and the current approximation is 10.4%, 3.3% and 5.0% respectively. Our simulation results suggest that the Markovian models are better than the deterministic periodic loss model. The Markov model in [CITATION_5] explicitly considers the TCP-Reno mode behaviour, while here we just use a simple approximation to account for the TCP-Reno mode behaviour. However, in spite of this we see that the Markov model in [CITATION_6] performs only marginally better than the current Markovian approximation that we use in this paper.",
